  <h3 class="c-left c-font-lowercase c-font-sbold">International</h3>

  <p>The outbreak of the SARS-CoV-2 virus, commonly known as Coronavirus, which began at a small city of China towards the end
    of 2019, and rapidly spread throughout the globe, to an extent that the World Health Organization reported over 13 million cases
    worldwide, including the sad passing of over a half million people. Until the first fortnight of July, countries with highest number
    of infected were the USA, Brazil, India, Russia, Peru, Chile and Mexico.</p>

  <p>Collaterally, the global economic performance has experienced a significant slowdown, leading institutions such as the International
    Monetary Fund to project that by 2020 the world's GDP will contract by 4.9% YoY. However, a "flattening of the propagation curve" is
    beginning to be observed in certain regions of Europe and in other continents, so if this behavior is replicated by a number countries,
    a recovery of ~5.4% could be expected in 2021, according to the same agency.</p>

  <p>Likewise, significant progress has been recorded in the development of a vaccine against COVID-19, as in Russia, one of the drug trials
    will be undergoing phase III (open to public but in a controlled environment) soon; while in the United States another possible vaccine is
    approaching the conclusion of its human trial phase; thus providing a more positive outlook for global population.</p>

  <h3 class="c-left c-font-lowercase c-font-sbold">National</h3>

  <p>In Mexico, the lockdown measures implemented by the Federal Government continue to reflect on the economic dynamism, posting an unprecedented
    plummet 19.9% YoY of in the monthly index of economic activity and a annual 17.9% drop in the SSS of the stores affiliated to The National Association
    of Supermarkets and Department Stores during June; therefore, the Bank of Mexico conducted a cut, once again, to its reference rate, now of 50 basis points
    to a level of 5.0% as of June 30<sup>th</sup>, 2020.</p>

  <p>Moreover, it is expected that through the enter into force of the new UMSCA agreement, a higher amount of foreign direct investment will be attracted in order
    to boost the economy during its reactivation process, which began during the six month of the year following the termination of the “National Days of Healthy Distance”.</p>

  <h3 class="c-left c-font-lowercase c-font-sbold">Industry</h3>

